# Tooling

## Environment setup (conda + Poetry + `.venv`)

**conda** controls the Python interpreter version. **Poetry** manages all Python packages via `pyproject.toml` and `poetry.lock`. A project-local **`.venv`** is created explicitly so the toolchain (pyright, ruff, pre-commit) is always self-contained and works without conda being activated.

### Why `.venv` is created explicitly

When poetry is installed inside a conda env, it detects the conda env as its virtualenv and will not create `.venv` automatically — even with `virtualenvs.in-project true`. To guarantee a project-local `.venv`, create it directly:

```bash
conda activate <env-name>           # activate the conda env for the right Python version
python -m venv .venv                # create .venv using the conda Python
poetry env use .venv/bin/python     # tell Poetry to use this .venv
poetry install                      # install all deps into .venv
```

After this, `.venv` is the single toolchain home. All `make` targets, pre-commit hooks, and pyright use it. Conda only needs to be activated when running live-infra flows (see **Tooling vs runtime env** below).

### First-time setup: `make setup`

Every service repo provides a `scripts/setup_dev.sh` and a `make setup` target that runs it. This is the single onboarding command:

```bash
make setup   # run once after cloning
```

Canonical `scripts/setup_dev.sh`:
```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

echo "[setup] Creating .venv with current conda Python..."
python -m venv .venv

echo "[setup] Registering .venv with Poetry..."
poetry env use .venv/bin/python

echo "[setup] Installing dependencies..."
poetry install

echo "[setup] Installing pre-commit hooks..."
.venv/bin/pre-commit install

echo "[setup] Done. Run 'make check' to verify."
```

Make target:
```makefile
setup:
	@bash scripts/setup_dev.sh
```

`scripts/setup_dev.sh` is committed to the repo. README setup instructions point here — not to a sequence of manual commands.

### Tooling vs runtime env

| Context | Env needed | How to run |
|---------|-----------|------------|
| `make check`, pyright, ruff, pre-commit | `.venv` only — no conda activation | `make check` from any shell |
| `pytest` (unit, no live infra) | `.venv` only | `make test` |
| `verify_all` (pure Python, live HTTP APIs) | `.venv` only | `.venv/bin/python -m tests.verify.verify_all` |
| `verify_all` (needs native conda packages) | conda env | `conda run -n <env-name> .venv/bin/python -m tests.verify.verify_all` |

The toolchain is fully self-contained in `.venv`. The `verify_all` invocation is service-specific — document the exact command in `tests/README.md`. **`conda activate` does not work inside Makefile targets** — use `conda run -n <env>` when conda env access is needed. The `verify` target is intentionally absent from the canonical Makefile: invocation varies per service and belongs in `tests/README.md`.

